However, Ganguly et al. [37] have shown that if a suitable spacer can be accommodated between fluorophore and MNP so that fluorophore and MNP remain at certain distance, the fluorescence of fluorophore can be enhanced. It is worthwhile to mention that for CTAB capped AuNPs no enhancement is observed. This is due to the fact that CTAB is not the suitable spacer to bring the enhancement effect. That is why CTAB is removed by repetitive washing to avoid any interference. Here we have judiciously introduced long-chain aliphatic thiols (1-octanethiol, 1-decanethiol, 1-dodecadecanethiol, 1-tetradecanethiol, 1-hexadecanethiol, 1-octadecanethiol represented as CnSH: n
                        =8, 10, 12, 14, 16, 18, respectively) as spacers. AuNPs have inherent affinity towards thiol group (SH) [38]. When thiols are added to AuNPs there occurs a conjugation between –SH and Au surface. CnSH also act as stabilizing agents. Thiol functionalized NS particles show absorption peaks at ~530nm and NR show peaks at ~550nm and ~750nm indicating that particles are stabilized and conjugated (Fig. S4). The peak shifting can be explained by the alteration of dielectric constant due to the presence of thiols of different chain length [38]. When a long-chain thiol (with different refractive indices) is attached to the Au surface, the homogeneity of the system is lost and the ligand sphere provides a dielectric coating on the metal surface. Thus a red shift of SPR band is observed. May be the thiol linkage is nonspecific as well as covalent in nature [36]. Also FTIR spectrum shows a weak peak at 432cm−1. This indicates the presence of weak AuS interaction (Fig. S5). However, the TEM image does not clearly exhibit the actual separation between carbon dots and gold nanoparticles. This is due to smaller size of CDAs in comparison to AuNPs. The thiol capped AuNPs are then added to CDA solution individually. Interestingly, thiol capped AuNP added CDA solution showed increased fluorescence when excited at 360nm. The phenomenon of increment of fluorescence is termed as gold enhanced fluorescence (GEF). Increment in fluorescence intensity has been observed to be dependent on the chain length of thiol (Fig. 4
                        ). As the chain length increases from C8SH to C18SH, the distance between thiol capped Au(0) surface and CDA increases, so also the fluorescence of CDA increases. We find maximum enhancement for 1-octadecanethiol. Now, the excitation wavelength is changed to 380nm and 400nm (Fig. S6). It is observed that with longer excitation wavelength, the enhancement of fluorescence intensity becomes less prominent. This goes well with the free space condition where emission intensity is decreased with the increase in excitation wavelength. Such phenomenon was previously reported by Dragon and Geddes [39]. They termed this condition as excitation volumetric effect (EVE).

This phenomenon has been successfully utilized for sulfide ion sensing in aqueous medium via ‘Turn Off’ phenomenon. For this purpose we use NS-C18SH-CDA. Upon addition of different anions in NS-C18SH-CDA solution individually, sulfide ions show significant quenching leaving aside other interfering ions like thiosulfate and iodide [42] (Fig. 9
                        ). Even in the presence of other ions, sulfide mediated quenching persists (Fig. 9). Thus NS-C18SH-CDA becomes an intriguing platform for selective sulfide sensing in aqueous solution. Fluorescence intensity of NS-C18SH-CDA solution decreases monotonously with the increase in the sulfide ion without altering emission maxima. A linear relation is obtained between the relative fluorescence intensity of NS-C18SH-CDA with/without sulfide ion and concentration of sulfide ion within the range of 0.3μM–0.3mM (R2
                        =0.9734). Sulfide ion can be detected down to 3.3nM using the prescribed method as shown in Fig. 9E and F.

The use of CDs in MEF is further confirmed by using silver(0) nanoparticles (AgNPs). This method is termed as silver enhanced fluorescence (SEF). AgNPs are synthesized by reducing silver nitrate with sodium borohydride. Here also the CDA shows quenching in the presence of AgNP. Then spacers are used to see the effect of spacers. It is established that AuS interaction is more pronounced than AuN interaction whereas AgN interaction is distinct than AgS interaction in accordance with hard-soft acid-base theory [37,38]. Hence, long-chain aliphatic amines (CxNH, x
                        =10, 12, 14, 16, for decylamine, dodecylamine, tetradecylamine, hexadecylamine) are used as spacers. The as-synthesized AgNPs are conjugated with long-chain aliphatic amines simply by incubating AgNPs in amine solution for one day. Then addition of CDA solution to amine-conjugated AgNP solution (AgNP-CxNH) shows chain length dependent enhancement in fluorescence (Fig. 10
                        ). In this case, maximum 5 fold enhancement is observed for hexadecylamine and quantum yield becomes 4.09%. In this case also the intensity of enhancement is decreased on increasing excitation wavelength following the theory of EVE. (Fig. S9). Thus CDAs are proved to be an efficient fluorophore for MEF.
